{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585435"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:12:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:12:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14974"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14974"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.07,0.02,0.85,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7662"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66468"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7662"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14974"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51919"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"7874"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18734"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18737"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66468"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is correct regarding Hodgkin\u0027s lymphoma?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["There are over 30 subtypes","Natural killer cells can be involved","It mainly affects the lower body","Reed-Sternberg cells are seen histologically","It makes up 85% of lymphomas"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReed-Sternberg cells are seen histologically\u003C/strong\u003E in Hodgkin\u0027s lymphoma. These are large, abnormal cells with a characteristic appearance, often described as having a \u0027owl-eye\u0027 appearance due to their bi-lobed nucleus and prominent nucleoli. The presence of these cells is a key diagnostic feature of Hodgkin\u0027s lymphoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThere are over 30 subtypes\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Hodgkin\u0027s lymphoma is classified into a few subtypes, primarily nodular sclerosis, mixed cellularity, lymphocyte-rich, and lymphocyte-depleted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENatural killer cells can be involved\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Hodgkin\u0027s lymphoma is primarily a B-cell malignancy, and natural killer cells are not typically involved in its pathogenesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt mainly affects the lower body\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Hodgkin\u0027s lymphoma often presents with lymphadenopathy in the upper body, such as the neck, chest, or underarms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt makes up 85% of lymphomas\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Hodgkin\u0027s lymphoma is less common than non-Hodgkin\u0027s lymphoma, making up a smaller percentage of all lymphomas.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hodgkin\u0027s lymphoma is characterised by the presence of Reed-Sternberg cells on histological examination.","Hodgkin\u0027s lymphoma is less common than non-Hodgkin\u0027s lymphoma, making up a smaller percentage of all lymphomas.","Hodgkin\u0027s lymphoma typically presents with lymphadenopathy in the upper body, such as the neck, chest, or underarms."],"references":["Bona, C. A., \u0026 Bonilla, F. A. (2019). Textbook of immunology. CRC press","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences",